messages.content: not related to bittensor, but since you asked.

I imagine Bittensor is mostly using the blockchain as an immutable ledger, and leveraging this ledger to craft incentives for players to ‘work’ in a certain direction. 

Polkadot is quite a bit different to Bitcoins proof of work. With proof of stake, ‘folks’ essentially put up capital (and earn capital) in order to have the ability to validate the information that gets entered into each block. With Polkadots incentives/punishments the folks validating blocks have a heavy risk/reward for providing honest blocks. Dishonest block validators don’t get rewarded with any income (and essentially lose money) or they can even be punished with whole loss of funds. 

Google the ‘Nakamoto coefficient’ it’s a sort of industry standard to measure how robust/decentralized/secure a block chain is. Polkadot is miles ahead of any other proof of stake. 

Proof of stake’s vulnerabilities are basically associated with capital. Someone ‘buys’ enough tokens (and validating capacity) to set up >50% of the validating portion of the blockchain and then they could attempt to perform a synchronized ’attack’ on the information that gets inserted into the blocks (then they essential control what gets documented in the ledger of the blockchain). 

Bittensor is a fledgling (but incredibly promising project) with a ‘relatively’ smaller size when compared to Polkadot. It would be much easier/cheaper to hijack the block info on a smaller chain as it would require considerably less capital.

Polkadot's dynamic forkless upgrades (that can occur/be implemented with zero down time) can essentially evolve/adapt to currently unknown threats or markets.

In therory no one owns/controls it. There’s no one to target in order to force it to ‘comply’. Not even Gavin Wood or Parity own it. Much like OpenTensor and Bittensor.

Bittensor definitely doesn’t need Polkadot. It just adds a whole spectrum of robustness that’ll allow participants that use Bittensor the capacity to not have to ‘trust’ the chain as much. Plus the whole interoperability benefits are staggering. The underlying tech in Polkadots XCMv3 is the closest thing to Web3 ‘internet magic’ that I’ve come across to date.
